,"meanings":["English:  see  Swain   and  compare  Swan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Swan","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>swon(e)</i>, northern Middle English <i>swan(e)</i> ‘swineherd; peasant; male servant’ (Old English <i>swān</i>). Compare   Swain   2, with which this name was thoroughly confused.","English: occasionally perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>swan</i>, <i>swon</i> ‘swan’. In the Middle Ages, the swan was taken as a symbol of false pride, and, according to Chaucer, jealousy. Compare   Kite  ,   Nightingale  , and   Pye  .","English: from the Middle English and Older Scots personal name <i>Swan</i>, an Anglicized form of Old Norse <i>Sveinn</i>. Compare   Swain   1."]},{"name":"Swain","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Swain</i>, <i>Swein</i> (Old Norse <i>Sveinn</i>, <i>Sven</i>, from <i>sveinn</i> ‘lad’).","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>swein</i> ‘servant, attendant; boy, young man’ (Old Norse <i>sveinn</i>). The word could also denote a swineherd or a peasant in general. The name was thoroughly confused with   Swan   1.","Irish: when not the English name, possibly an Anglicized form of <b>Mac Suibhne</b>; see   McSwain  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Swane was born in 1355, in Stanthorne, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Swane. He married Agnes Heth in 1380, in Stanthorne, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1355–":"1355–Surnud","1355–Male":"1355–Surnud","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1382–1479":"1382–1479","–Male":"Surnud","1479":"1479","1355":"1355","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","Stanthorne, Cheshire, England":"Stanthorne, Cheshire, England","Stanthorne, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stanthorne, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stanthorne, Chesire, England":"Stanthorne, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1355–":"1355–Kuollut","1355–Male":"1355–Kuollut","1360–Female":"1360–Kuollut","1382–1479":"1382–1479","–Male":"Kuollut","1479":"1479","1355":"1355","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","Stanthorne, Cheshire, England":"Stanthorne, Cheshire, England","Stanthorne, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stanthorne, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Stanthorne, Chesire, England":"Stanthorne, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1355–":"1355–Décédé","1355–Male":"1355–Décédé","1360–Female":"1360–Décédée","1382–1479":"1382–1479","–Male":"Décédé","1479":"1479","1355":"1355","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","Stanthorne, Cheshire, England":"Stanthorne, Cheshire, Angleterre","Stanthorne, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stanthorne, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Stanthorne, Chesire, England":"Stanthorne, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Robert Swane est né en 1355, à Stanthorne, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de Swane. Il a épousé Agnes Heth en 1380, à Stanthorne, Cheshire,